**suggestion**: The `_ => {}` arm silently discards `Failure` and `ShutdownRequested` events during the shutdown draining phase. If the health monitor sends a late `Failure` (poll tick resolves before cancellation), the affected component stays in `ShuttingDown` indefinitely. The `global_shutdown_timeout` (60s default) eventually catches it, but the manager has the information to finish immediately and doesn't act on it.

Consider handling `Failure` here by setting the component's phase to `Died`, same as the `Died` arm above:
```rust
ComponentEvent::Failure { tag, reason } => {
    if let Some(s) = self.components.get_mut(&tag) {
        s.phase = ShutdownPhase::Died;
        let elapsed = shutdown_clock.elapsed();
        metrics::emit_component_shutdown_duration(&name, &tag, "died", elapsed.as_secs_f64());
        metrics::emit_component_shutdown_result(&name, &tag, "died");
    }
    first_failure = first_failure.or(Some(LifecycleError::ComponentFailure { tag, reason }));
}
```

**suggestion**: All `emit_*` functions call `.to_string()` on `&str` label values, forcing a heap allocation on every call. The `metrics` macros accept `&str` directly via `Into<SharedString>`. This function is the hottest path (called every poll tick per component).

```suggestion
pub(crate) fn emit_component_healthy(service_name: &str, component: &str, healthy: bool) {
